      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Top 5 Ligand Classes by Number of Ligands\n\n| Rank | Ligand Class | Ligand Count | % of Total |\n|:----:|:-------------|:------------:|:----------:|\n| 1 | Ligands not selected | 1,339 | 23.3% |\n| 2 | Amino Acids | 297 | 5.2% |\n| 3 | Aliphatic amines | 250 | 4.4% |\n| 4 | Pyridines (azines) | 248 | 4.3% |\n| 5 | Carboxylic acids | 182 | 3.2% |\n\n**Chemistry insight:** The largest \"real\" class is **Amino Acids** (297 ligands), which makes sense given their biological importance and the extensive study of metal–amino acid complexation in biochemistry. **Aliphatic amines** and **Pyridines** follow closely — both are classic nitrogen-donor ligands widely used in coordination chemistry. The top-ranked entry, \"Ligands not selected,\" is a catch-all category for ligands that haven't been assigned to a specific structural class, accounting for nearly a quarter of all entries.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
